        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1956-09-28T18:29:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1956-09-28T18:29:00-05:00" n="273"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d273">
                <head>273. Telegram From <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the <gloss
                        type="to">Embassy in Bolivia</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d273fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 724.00/9–2856. Secret; <gloss target="#t_niact1">Niact</gloss>.
                        Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_BMM1">Bernbaum</persName>, <persName
                            corresp="#p_BEO1">Briggs</persName>, and <persName corresp="#p_SEV1"
                            >Siracusa</persName> and initialed by <persName corresp="#p_RRRJ1"
                            >Rubottom</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1956-09-28T19:29:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 28, 1956—7:29 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>96. Department agrees objectives of action recommended <gloss target="#t_Embtel1"
                        >Embtel</gloss> 93<note n="2" xml:id="d273fn2">
                        <hi rend="italic">Supra</hi>.</note> but doubts whether prospects of success
                    justify risks involved, including misinterpretation as intervention in internal
                    Bolivian affairs. You may state following if approached by Bolivian leaders or
                    if opportunity otherwise presented discuss problem with them.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>(1)</label>
                    <item>Department concerned over indications possible imminent change in
                        Government but recognizes this internal Bolivian matter.</item>
                    <label>(2)</label>
                    <item>Any changes would naturally require thorough evaluation in terms US
                        policies.</item>
                </list>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_FYI1">FYI</gloss> basic elements such evaluation would be (1)
                    that communists or communist sympathizers do not participate in or have
                    influence in government; and (2) that stabilization program be carried out.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Dulles</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
